Laravel has some native helpers that can help you achieve this goal. The main is [`Str::slug`](https://laravel.com/docs/6.x/helpers#method-str-slug) method.

This is its source code:

```php
/**
 * Generate a URL friendly &quot;slug&quot; from a given string.
 *
 * @param  string  $title
 * @param  string  $separator
 * @param  string|null  $language
 * @return string
 */
public static function slug($title, $separator = &#39;-&#39;, $language = &#39;en&#39;)
{
    $title = $language ? static::ascii($title, $language) : $title;

    // Convert all dashes/underscores into separator
    $flip = $separator === &#39;-&#39; ? &#39;_&#39; : &#39;-&#39;;
    $title = preg_replace(&#39;![&#39;.preg_quote($flip).&#39;]+!u&#39;, $separator, $title);

    // Replace @ with the word &#39;at&#39;
    $title = str_replace(&#39;@&#39;, $separator.&#39;at&#39;.$separator, $title);

    // Remove all characters that are not the separator, letters, numbers, or whitespace.
    $title = preg_replace(&#39;![^&#39;.preg_quote($separator).&#39;\pL\pN\s]+!u&#39;, &#39;&#39;, static::lower($title));

    // Replace all separator characters and whitespace by a single separator
    $title = preg_replace(&#39;![&#39;.preg_quote($separator).&#39;\s]+!u&#39;, $separator, $title);

    return trim($title, $separator);
}
```

This helper is enough to generate a SEO Friendly URL, but this answer only to the first and second bullet point. For the rest I think that the best solution is to use an [Accessor](https://laravel.com/docs/6.x/eloquent-mutators#defining-an-accessor) in your `Food` class.

